# [[must]], to do or have with certainty
# {{lb|fr|transitive}} to [[owe]] (money, obligation and etc)
# {{lb|fr|literary|intransitive|in imperfect subjunctive, with inversion of subject}} (even) if it is [[necessary]] (+ infinitive)
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1842|author=w:George Sand|title=Consuelo
|passage=Eh bien, se dit-elle, j'irai, '''dussé'''-je affronter les dangers réels [...].|t=Well, she said to herself, I'll go, '''even if''' I '''have to''' face real danger.}}
#* {{quote-book|fr|year=1819|author=Pierre Capelle|title=Nouvelle Encyclopédie poétique -Tome XVIII|publisher=Ferra|url=https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nouvelle_Encyclop%C3%A9die_po%C3%A9tique,_tome_XVIII,_1819.djvu/112|page=112|text=Et, quand les sots sont les plus applaudis,<br/>'''Dussé'''-je en tout passer pour une grue,<br/>Faveur se cache aussitôt qu’obtenue,<br/>Tant j’aime encor comme on aimait jadis.|t=&, when the fools are the most applauded,<br/>'''Were''' I to pass for everthing as a crane,<br/>Favour hides as soon as it's obtained,<br/>So many I love still as we loved in days of yore.}}
#* {{quote-book|fr|year=18--|author=Charles Paul de Kock|title=L'ânè a M. Martin|chapter=XIV|url=https://archive.org/details/lnmmartinpar00kockuoft/page/132/mode/2up?q=dussions|publisher=Jules Rouff et C<sup>ie</sup>, Paris|page=132|text=Oui, oui, répond-on de tous côtés, nous vous attendrons... oh ! nous ne bougerons pas d'ici que vous ne soyez revenu, '''dussions'''-nous même y passer la nuit !|t="Yes, yes," they answered from all sides, "we will wait for you...oh! we will not move from here if you do not return, '''even if''' we have to spend the night!}}
# {{lb|fr|reflexive|~ '''de'''}} to have a [[duty]] to
#* {{quote-book|fr|title=Constitution française, présentée au roi par l'Assemblée nationale, le 3 septembre 1791|trans-title=French constitution, presented to the King by the National Assembly on 3 September 1791|year=1791|author=Louis XVI|location=Dijon|publisher=Imprimerie de P. Causse|page=75|text=Aujourd'hui je '''dois''' aux intérêts de la nation, je me '''dois''' à moi-même de faire connoître mes motifs.|translation=Today, I '''owe''' to the interests of the nation, [so] I '''owe''' it to myself to make my motives known.|chapter=Message du roi, à l'Assemblée nationale, le 13 septembre 1791|trans-chapter=Message of the King to the National Assembly on 13 September 1791}}

====Usage notes====
* The circumflex accent applied to the {{m|fr||u}} in the past participle {{m|fr|dû}} serves only to distinguish it from the prepositive {{m|fr|du|t=of the}}. As such, the circumflex is omitted in the participle's other inflections: {{m|fr|due|g=f-s}}, {{m|fr|dus|g=m-p}}, {{m|fr|dues|g=f-p}}. The diacritic is likewise omitted in the derived adjective {{m|fr|indu|t=undue, unwarranted}} and its inflected forms, but retained in the adverbial derivative {{m|fr|dûment}} and {{m|fr|indûment}}, where it serves as an etymological marker signaling the elision of the letter {{m|fr||e}} from the older spelling {{m|fr||duement}}. These latter, however, may be rendered {{m|fr|dument}} and {{m|fr|indument}} according to the [[Appendix:French spelling reforms of 1990|orthographic reforms]] advanced by the {{m|fr||Conseil supérieur de la langue française}} and approved by the {{m|fr||Académie française}} in 1990.
* In negative constructions (e.g. {{m|fr||ne pas devoir}} and {{m|fr||ne plus devoir}}), the sense becomes "must not," "should not", etc.
*: {{uxi|fr|Je '''dois''' y aller.|I must go. / I have to go.}}
*: {{uxi|fr|Je '''ne dois pas''' y aller.|I must not go.}}
*: {{uxi|fr|'''Ne devriez'''-vous pas vous en aller ?|Shouldn't you go away?}}
*: {{ux|fr|Ça '''ne devrait plus''' vous poser de problèmes.|That should no longer pose any problems.}}

